        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1955-08-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1955-08-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="125"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d125">
                <head>125. Telegram 589 from Geneva<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d125fn1"
                        >Source: Department of State, Central Files, 611.93/8–2355. Secret; Very
                        Limited Distribution.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Geneva</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1955-08-23"
                            >August 23, 1955, 2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <pb facs="d125-1" n="1" type="facsimile" xml:id="d125-1"/>
                <p>589. From <persName corresp="#p_JUA_1">Johnson</persName>.</p>
                <p>Additional minor sidelights on dinner with <persName corresp="#p_WP_1"
                        >Wang</persName> last night:</p>
                <p>Particularly inquired about Bedell Smith’s health and later made point of saying
                    “better relations began” when Smith spoke to <persName corresp="#p_CEL_1"
                        >Chou</persName> in buffet at last year’s Geneva Conference expressing hope
                    relations might improve.</p>
                <p>Gave usual line on civil war events but with noticeable restraint in treatment
                    Kuomintang and Chiang Kai-shek.</p>
                <p>Were thankful and appreciative American aid to China during World War II even
                    though none received by Communists as it constituted contribution national
                    strength in fight against Japan.</p>
                <p>In reply my raising Communist bloc characteristics of super-secrecy and
                    hypersensitivity to criticism as major barriers to fruitful interchange persons
                    and ideas which he had been urging, he did not contest but implied improvement
                    this regard under way. He was very quick reject any implication Chinese
                    Communists identification with satellites when I cited personal experience in
                    Czechoslovakia.</p>
                <p>Rejected my suggestion China lacked natural resources, only problem was
                    extraction.</p>
                <p>Noted full texts Secretary’s and President’s statements and speeches on Far East
                    published in Chinese Communist press.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GFC_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Gowen</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
